messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full HTTP request path:
- /printshops/{id}/pricetable/papers

HTTP methods acceptance (based on the code):
- all HTTP methods acceptable: false
- HEAD: false
- POST: true
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: false
- PUT: true
- DELETE: false
- PATCH: false

Explanation:
- In PriceTableController there is no class-level @RequestMapping, so the full path is exactly the method-level mapping value: "/printshops/{id}/pricetable/papers".
- The controller defines two handler methods for that exact path:
  - addNewPaperItem(...) annotated with @RequestMapping(value = "/printshops/{id}/pricetable/papers", method = RequestMethod.POST)
  - editPaperItem(...) annotated with @RequestMapping(value = "/printshops/{id}/pricetable/papers", method = RequestMethod.PUT)
- No other methods in the source map to this exact path. Therefore, based strictly on the code, only POST and PUT are accepted.
- Per your instruction to base acceptability on the code (not on runtime/framework behavior), I marked OPTIONS/HEAD/TRACE/GET/DELETE/PATCH as not acceptable because they are not explicitly mapped in the source. (Although some frameworks may auto-handle OPTIONS or HEAD in practice, that was not considered here.)
